Fragment from the minified library file we are importing (the place where `exports` is not minified as in few other places it is mangled):

```
function (e, t, n) { "use strict"; (function (e) { var r = n(10), o = n(92), i = "object" == typeof exports && exports && !exports.nodeType && exports, a = i && "object" == typeof e && e && !e.nodeType && e, s = a && a.exports === i ? r.a.Buffer : void 0, u = (s ? s.isBuffer : void 0) || o.a; t.a = u }).call(this, n(61)(e)) }
```

So far my attempts at creating a small repro have not been successful.

optimization.sideEffects have to be enabled and the issue is triggered only when multiple entries both reference the library, however, only indirectly via multiple re-exports (we have `sideEffects: false` enabled for all of our own modules as well).

Seeing how this is marked as critical bug now - if you will need the reproduction, please let me know I will try to more aggressively delete stuff to get somewhere. So far I have not been able to guess how to reproduce the issue in a fresh project, so I would need to keep trimming our large monorepo.

One more note - splitChunks do not impact this, disabled all of our cacheGroups (vendors and commons) and the same result.

As @Knagis points out, setting `optimization: { sideEffects: false }` is the way to work around this issue. In my project, we have reactstrap@8.5.1's dependencies falling prey to this bug.

hmm just `import { Collapse, DropdownToggle } from "reactstrap"` doesn't lead to this problem.

@sokra I'll try to get a minimal repro together tonight. We have another lib that imports all of reactstrap (https://github.com/Availity/availity-reactstrap-validation). This other lib is in its own chunk.
Still unable to reproduce, but it seem to be caused by `module.exports = exports["default"]` under some weird conditions...
Does the error still happen when `optimization.concatenateModules: false` is used?
in my case reproduces with `concatenateModules: false`
Do you have any other custom `optimization` config?
no, I have splitChunks, but tried with them disabled and had the same result.
Ok after long trying I'm able to reproduce it...

Ok it's a little bit tricky to fix, but the good news is that this error means that these modules are unused and shouldn't be in the chunks so bundle size will shink in your cases. As workaround also try `optimization.usedExports: "global"`, that should have the lowest cost.

issue.title: fix unused modules in chunk when optimizing runtime-specific

repository.name: webpack
repository.description: A bundler for javascript and friends. Packs many modules into a few bundled assets. Code Splitting allows for loading parts of the application on demand. Through "loaders", modules can be CommonJs, AMD, ES6 modules, CSS, Images, JSON, Coffeescript, LESS, ... and your custom stuff.
